{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774293509,"nonce":"fsCDFHDJT9m1a43xaNmibfPinFE=","message":"## Additional note: peak velocity with random/constant fields\n\nThe curl-field velocity suppression (perturbation force proportional to velocity → gradient avoids high-v paths) is real but NOT the whole story. Random and constant fields also fail to produce peak velocity increases, confirming the loss function structure is the primary bottleneck independent of perturbation type.\n\nThe accumulating-cost / movement-time penalty (geometric discount penalizing late arrival) remains the most direct fix. See also issue 84ee4ff (APT/CVaR) and c05998e (Part 2.5 experiment) for worst-case training as a complementary approach.","files":null}]}